result.execSummary:
On one or more charges, the deferred prosecution or sentencing agreement(s) on this case were fulfilled, and the charge(s) were dismissed.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Jordan D. Frost in court with attorney Jared Redfield. David R. Knaapen appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
10:41 a.m.  Court calls the case. 

Plea questionnaire/Agreement filed.
Prosecutor states plea agreement.  VIP program recommendation. 
Attorney for Defendant concurs with agreement stated.

Defendant enters a plea of: Count 1 - NO CONTEST

Court questions Defendant regarding plea.
Court informs Defendant of Constitutional Rights. Court advises Defendant of Elements State must prove for the Charge.
Court questions Attorney for Defendant.
Court finds Defendant's Plea is freely, voluntarily and intelligently made.
Attorneys stipulate that there is factual basis for the charge(s).

BY THE COURT:
Court finds a sufficient factual basis to support the charge(s).
Court finds the defendant guilty of Count 1.  Clerk directed to withhold entry of judgment of conviction. 
Count 2 is dismissed and read-in. 

Atty Knaapen makes sentencing arguments to the Court. 
Atty Redfield makes sentencing arguments to the Court. 

BY THE COURT:
Count 1 - 
Placed in the VIP program for 6 months: 
Perform 20 hours community service preferrabley with the Portage 
Particaipate in ACS groups and day report as requested which may include submitting samples for testing for controlled substances or alcohol. 
Complete AODA & comply with treatment recommendations.
Do not possess/consume controlled substances without a valid prescription and be taken according to the prescription. 
Do not possess any drug paraphernalia. 
Do not associate with any persons possessing or consuming illegal controlled substances.
Participate in any other community based services as deemed appropriate by the VIP program director. 
Upon successful completion, the State will file a dismissal.
